<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06236139 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06236139 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  The Supreme Court of Canada ruled Thursday that the sexual history of rapevictims may be offered as evidence in court at the trial judge's discretion.The 7-2 decision struck down part of a 1983 law shielding rape victims fromintrusive questioning about their sexual behavior. The judge may allow suchevidence, the court said, where it is useful and is not being raised simply toimply that the victim was more likely to have consented to the sexual conductor is a less believable witness.;   Women's groups immediately criticized thedecision, saying it would discourage women from reporting rapes. In the UnitedStates, every state has adopted a shield law generally prohibiting theintroduction of evidence about a victim's sexual history.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CANADA DILUTES RAPE VICTIMS' SHIELD STATUTE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910823  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  16A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  127  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, August 23, 199100236139,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>